# AiDoc RAG Services — Setup and Usage

AiDoc provides centralized RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation) indexes hosted on `dedge-server` via Python HTTP servers. These give Cursor and Ollama access to DB2, Visual COBOL, and Dedge source documentation without needing local copies.

## Available RAGs

| RAG | Port | Description |
|-----|------|-------------|
| `db2-docs` | 8484 | DB2 12.1 LUW manuals |
| `visual-cobol-docs` | 8485 | Visual COBOL 11 compiler messages |
| `Dedge-code` | 8486 | Dedge source code (COBOL, C#, PowerShell, Python, Node) and DB2 schemas |

Registry endpoint (no auth): `http://dedge-server:8484/rags`

## Cursor Setup (one-time)

Run the setup script from `DedgePsh\DevTools\CodingTools`:

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\CodingTools\Setup-CursorRagNew\Setup-CursorRagNew.ps1"
```

Or from deployed location:

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "$env:OptPath\DedgePshApps\Setup-CursorRagNew\Setup-CursorRagNew.ps1"
```

This auto-discovers RAGs from the AiDocNew API, creates a lightweight Python venv in `~/.cursor/rag-proxy/`, and updates `~/.cursor/mcp.json`. Restart Cursor after running.

**Important:** Always use the `*New` variants (`Setup-CursorRagNew`, `Setup-OllamaRagNew`), not the old `Setup-CursorRag` / `Setup-OllamaRag` scripts. The old scripts point to the legacy AiDoc architecture.

### Verify

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\CodingTools\Setup-CursorRagNew\Test-CursorRagNew.ps1"
```

### Revert

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\CodingTools\Setup-CursorRagNew\Setup-CursorRagNew.ps1" -Revert
```

## Ollama Setup (one-time)

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\CodingTools\Setup-OllamaRagNew\Setup-OllamaRagNew.ps1"
```

Restart PowerShell, then use:

```powershell
Ask-Rag "What does SQL30082N reason code 36 mean?"
Ask-Rag "COBCH0779 error" -Rag visual-cobol-docs
Ask-Rag "Deploy-Files" -Rag Dedge-code
```

### Verify

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\CodingTools\Setup-OllamaRagNew\Test-OllamaRagNew.ps1"
```

## Using RAGs in Cursor Chat

Each RAG appears as an MCP server with a `query_docs` tool. The agent calls them automatically based on the question topic:

- **DB2 questions** (SQL errors, security, configuration) → `db2-docs`
- **Visual COBOL questions** (compiler messages, language reference) → `visual-cobol-docs`
- **Dedge code questions** (where is a function, schema layout) → `Dedge-code`

Do not use `db2-docs` for COBOL questions or vice versa.

## How RAG Access Works

RAG services run as **Python HTTP servers directly** on `dedge-server` (ports 8484-8486). They are **unauthenticated** — no DedgeAuth, no JWT, no API keys. The Cursor MCP proxy and Ask-Rag function connect directly to these Python services over HTTP, bypassing the C# API entirely.

```
Developer Machine                          dedge-server
┌──────────────────┐                      ┌──────────────────┐
│ Cursor IDE       │                      │ Python HTTP RAGs  │
│  └─ MCP proxy ───┼── HTTP :8484-8486 ──►│  db2-docs         │
│     (stdio)      │                      │  visual-cobol-docs│
│                  │                      │  Dedge-code      │
│ PowerShell       │                      │                   │
│  └─ Ask-Rag ─────┼── HTTP :8484-8486 ──►│  (ChromaDB +      │
│     + Ollama     │                      │   ONNX embedding) │
└──────────────────┘                      └──────────────────┘
```

## Prerequisites

- Windows 11 / Windows Server 2025
- PowerShell 7+ (`pwsh.exe`)
- Python 3.11+ (Cursor setup only)
- Ollama installed from [ollama.com](https://ollama.com) (Ollama setup only)
- Network access to `dedge-server`
